:0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"While digging into latest failures in `ocramius/proxy-manager`, I found that psalm cannot infer types for `$a` in `is_a($a, class-string<T>, true)`.\r\n\r\nTake following example:\r\n\r\n * https://psalm.dev/r/c049cd03d3\r\n\r\nThe type inference detects `string`.\r\n\r\nWhen removing the templated type, and hardcoding `is_a($a, A::class, true)`, everything works as expected:\r\n\r\n * https://psalm.dev/r/b71fe908d1\r\n\r\nWhen using a manually crafted `@psalm-assert` function (instead of `\\assert(\\is_a(...))`, types seem to be inferred correctly:\r\n\r\n * https://psalm.dev/r/f2ec6a1ef8\r\n\r\nI found this code location affecting this:\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/vimeo/psalm/blob/f0fc9cce5fabdd1350363b960659d2977f478a55/src/Psalm/Internal/Analyzer/Statements/Expression/AssertionFinder.php#L1648-L1732\r\n\r\n\r\nGiven that `@psalm-assert` seems to work fine, maybe `is_a()` can be somehow translated into more primitive definitions?","closed_by":{"login":"muglug","id":2292638,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjIyOTI2Mzg=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/2292638?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/muglug","html_url":"https://github.com/muglug","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/muglug/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/muglug/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/muglug/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/muglug/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/muglug/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/muglug/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/muglug/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/muglug/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/muglug/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"reactions":{"url":"htt